content.html:
It‚Äôs Black History Month‚Ä¶

I‚Äôm going to say things that may make you uncomfortable. I feel kinda uncomfortable for *having to say them* every year (I shouldn‚Äôt; Black history is part of AMERICAN history, is it not?)

So buckle up, seats and tray tables in full and upright positions lads, it may be bumpy as we travel down this road.

First up‚Äì This Mastodon thread from the #Fediverse about how #EminentDomain was is used as a weapon to destroy mainly Black & Brown people‚Äôs neighborhoods in the name of progress and #gentrification.

(Also, this is another reason I‚Äôve always been pro-railroad and pro-transit. People cheer when a new subway line comes to their neighborhoods; how many times as anyone ever gotten excited over a damn freeway being built through their area, especially if they‚Äôre the ones being forced to move because of it?!)

summary.html:
@mekkaokereke@hachyderm.io As a #Atlanta resident living near I-20, seeing that before and after always hurts. My street literally dead ends into the side wall of the highway and I think about this destruction almost every day.

We need to demolish the freeway, reconnect the Atlanta street grid and build large amounts of affordable housing to begin to repair our city.

content.html:
And it gets better ‚Äî You can check EVERY SINGLE CITY in America where Dwight Eisenhower‚Äôs Interstate Program went into effect and damn near all of them involved bulldozing a Black neighborhood.

I‚Äôm from St Louis and every one of them got razed. I-70 thru the Northside, I-44/55 thru the Southside and even the unbuilt 22nd Street Expressway that was used as an excuse to tear down a lot of wealthy Black St Louis‚Äôs neighborhoods near downtown‚Ä¶ Even though it didn‚Äôt get built!

Same thing happened with the GA-410 Freeway as it came out of downtown. All those neighborhoods around Boulevard and Highland? Those were the black ones. But it never got built because the wealthy white population living north of Ponce De Leon wasn‚Äôt having it. So it got stalled out in court and ultimately never built. The project was officially cancelled in 1987. Instead they turned the right of way they already tore down into a street ‚Äî Freedom Parkway ‚Äî and now has property so expensive, none of the original residents could hope to live even around their old neighborhoods.

As a #GwinnettCounty GA resident, knowing I‚Äôm living on land I own, that used to be part of one of the biggest and oldest plantations and sharecroppers fields in the Atlanta metro area‚Ä¶ I OWN this little half an acre were my ancestors were forced against their will to create wealth for someone else‚Ä¶ Yet hundreds of years later is making my family money. And I had to work SO DAMN HARD just to be able to get this little half acre. I‚Äôm proud of myself, proud of my wife and family who sacrificed to get our little piece. But why is it so tough to get what should be so easy, a basic human right‚Äì the right to shelter?

If you work, you should have a place to live. Are you a minor? You should have a safe, dry place to lay your head. Are you an elder who has given years to the system? You should get a comfortable place to spend the rest of your days. No strings attached. End of story.

It makes me feel some kinda way. Bittersweet.
BTW there will be a local Black History Museum opening in time for Juneteenth this summer in Lilburn GA. These little nooks and crannies around Atlanta are also full of history. We need to learn, remember and treasure every piece of it.

content.html:
‚Ü©Ô∏è notes.tracydurnell.com/2023/02/02/super-psyched-to.html

Super psyched to cancel my gas service today! We replaced our old gas furnace and water heater with electric.

I miss our multihead heat pumps in Japan for this reason; each room gets their own HVAC source while other spaces like halls and closets get none ‚Äî only heating or cooling the part of the house you‚Äôre actually in also saves lots of money. So sure, blast the heat in the bedroom at night because you‚Äôre not paying to heat the kitchen, living room, den, etc‚Ä¶
And heat pumps are way more efficient so the newer ones heat and cool better for less energy.
At some point I will need to do this too as our lethargic central HVAC unit is UNDER the house in the crawl space (who‚Äôs bright idea was that anyway) and several zones of less than ideal climate are always nagging me this time of year.
